# IMP-0301

# Dependency Injection and Object Lifetime

Status: Draft

Version: 0.1

Depends on:

* IMP-0200 Hypervisor Service Interfaces
* IMP-0300 Hypervisor Bootstrap Sequence

---

# 1. Purpose

This document defines object construction, dependency injection and object lifetime within the AiDN Hypervisor.

The objective is to guarantee deterministic initialization, predictable ownership and testability.

---

# 2. Design Principles

### DI-1

Every service SHALL be created exactly once during Hypervisor bootstrap.

---

### DI-2

Business logic SHALL NEVER construct services.

---

### DI-3

Business logic SHALL depend only on interfaces.

---

### DI-4

Object lifetime SHALL be managed exclusively by the Bootstrap process.

---

# 3. Bootstrap Ownership

The Bootstrap process is the only component allowed to construct:

* services;
* repositories;
* event bus;
* storage;
* provider manager;
* schedulers;
* runtime managers;
* API servers.

No other package may construct these objects.

---

# 4. Construction Rules

Construction SHALL occur only through constructors.

Example:

```go id="tdo5fc"
func NewEndpointService(
    repo EndpointRepository,
    scheduler Scheduler,
    events EventBus,
    metrics MetricsService,
) EndpointService
```

Constructors SHALL return interfaces.

Constructors SHALL NOT start background work.

---

# 5. Forbidden Patterns

The following patterns are prohibited.

Creating services inside business logic:

```go id="7rbjlwm"
endpoint := NewEndpointService(...)
```

Also prohibited:

* global service instances;
* package-level mutable singletons;
* service locators;
* runtime dependency lookup;
* calling constructors after bootstrap.

---

# 6. Dependency Direction

Dependencies SHALL always point downward.

```text id="nsyjlwm"
API

↓

Services

↓

Repositories

↓

Storage
```

Reverse dependencies are prohibited.

---

# 7. Object Lifetime

Objects belong to one of four lifetime classes.

### Singleton

Created once.

Destroyed during shutdown.

Examples:

* EventBus
* Scheduler
* Wallet
* Validator
* Registry

---

### Session

Bound to an API request.

Destroyed after completion.

Examples:

* Request Context
* Authentication Context

---

### Task

Bound to a workload.

Destroyed after task completion.

Examples:

* Execution Context
* Validation Session

---

### Temporary

Created locally.

Never stored.

Destroyed immediately after use.

---

# 8. Service Responsibilities

Every service SHALL:

* expose exactly one interface;
* own its persistence;
* own its events;
* own its internal synchronization.

Services SHALL NOT own the lifetime of other services.

---

# 9. Dependency Injection

Dependencies SHALL be injected only through constructors.

Setter injection is prohibited.

Field injection is prohibited.

Reflection-based injection is prohibited.

---

# 10. Interface Ownership

Every package owns:

* one primary interface;
* one implementation;
* supporting types.

Implementations SHOULD remain private whenever possible.

---

# 11. Background Workers

Background workers SHALL be started explicitly during bootstrap.

Constructors SHALL NOT create goroutines.

Every background worker SHALL support graceful shutdown through context cancellation.

---

# 12. Testing

Every constructor SHALL allow creation using mock dependencies.

No constructor SHALL require real databases, Providers or network connections.

---

# 13. Design Invariants

Invariant 1

Bootstrap owns object creation.

---

Invariant 2

Constructors never start work.

---

Invariant 3

Business logic never calls constructors.

---

Invariant 4

Services own behavior.

Bootstrap owns lifetime.

---

Invariant 5

Every dependency is explicit.

Implicit dependencies are prohibited.
